Figure 2.4 illustrates the circuit symbols for the two BJT types, including the current directions and voltage polarities. In both cases, the terminal with the arrow is designated as the emitter, with the arrow indicating the direction of the emitter current. For the pnp BJT, where the primary current is due to holes, the arrow aligns with the hole flow direction. Conversely, in the npn BJT, where the primary current is due to electrons (which are negative), the emitter arrow points opposite to the internal electron flow.

