Regardless of the device type and operating mode, a BJT must always adhere to Kirchhoff's Current Law (KCL),
$$
\begin{equation*}
i_{E}=i_{C}+i_{B} \tag{2.2}
\end{equation*}
$$
When analyzing a BJT circuit, it is beneficial to encircle the device and treat it as a supernode.

The BJT demonstrates its distinctive capabilities when we disrupt the aforementioned equilibrium by applying appropriate voltages across its junctions. As previously stated, the most beneficial operating mode is the forward active (FA) mode, which is achieved by forward-biasing the B-E junction and reverse-biasing the B-C junction. Forward-biasing the B-E junction with a voltage $v_{B E}$ lowers the potential barrier that prevents electrons and holes from diffusing across the junction. Our focus is particularly on the region right at the base edge of the B-E SCL, designated as the origin of the $x$-axis in Fig. 2.5. According to the junction law discussed in relation to Eq. (1.51), applying $v_{B E}$ causes the electron concentration $n_{B}(0)$ at the SCL's edge to surge from its equilibrium value $n_{B 0}\left(\cong 2 \times 10^{2} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}\right)$ to a new value
$$
\begin{equation*}
n_{B}(0)=n_{B 0} e^{v_{B E} / V_{T}} \tag{2.7}
\end{equation*}
$$
where $V_{T}=k T / q$ represents the thermal voltage ( $V_{T}=25.9 \mathrm{mV} \cong 26 \mathrm{mV}$ at $T=300 \mathrm{~K}$ ). For instance, with a typical $v_{B E}=700 \mathrm{mV}$, $n_{B}(0)$ increases from $n_{B 0} \cong 2 \times 10^{2} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}$ to
$$
n_{B}(0) \cong\left(2 \times 10^{2}\right) e^{700 / 26} \cong\left(2 \times 10^{2}\right) \times 5 \times 10^{11}=10^{14} \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}
$$
This represents a significant rise! However, since $n_{B}(0) \ll p_{B 0}\left(\right.$ as $\left.10^{14} \ll 10^{18}\right)$, the predominant mobile charges remain holes. We term this scenario low-level injection (specifically, electron injection from the emitter).

Reverse-biasing the B-C junction with a voltage $v_{B C} \leq 0.2 \mathrm{~V}$, or equivalently, with a voltage $v_{C B} \geq 0.2 \mathrm{~V}$, again by the junction law, alters the existing electron concentration at the base-edge of the B-C SCL to a new value
$$
\begin{equation*}
n_{B}\left(W_{B}\right)=n_{B 0} e^{v_{B d} / V_{T}}=n_{B 0} e^{-v_{c c} / V_{T}} \tag{2.8}
\end{equation*}
$$
where $W_{B}$ signifies the effective base width, defined as the distance between the base edges of the two SCLs. With a reverse bias as low as 0.2 V, Eq. (2.8) yields $n_{B}\left(W_{B}\right) \cong\left(2 \times 10^{2}\right) e^{-200 / 26} \cong\left(2 \times 10^{2}\right) / 2191 \cong 0.1 \mathrm{~cm}^{-3}$, which is practically negligible compared to other concentrations. Given that the base is intentionally fabricated to be very thin, the electron distribution in the base assumes a linear profile, as illustrated. If the base were wider, the distribution profile would exhibit an exponential decay, implying that most electrons would recombine in the base and fail to reach the collector. This underscores the importance of fabricating the base very thin (typically a fraction of a $\mu \mathrm{m}$).

