Figure 2.11 depicts the pertinent currents within a pnp BJT. When compared to its npn counterpart in Fig. 2.6, a notable resemblance is observed, aside from the swapping of holes and electrons, along with a reversal in voltage polarities and current directions. As previously discussed, the primary process involves the flow of holes from the emitter, through the slender base, and into the collector. Without reiterating the derivations, we can directly apply the results from the npn BJT and express
$$
\begin{equation*}
i_{C}=I_{s} e^{v_{E B} / V_{T}} \tag{2.16}
\end{equation*}
$$
where
$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{s}=A_{E} \times \frac{1}{W_{B}} \times n_{i}^{2}(T) \times \frac{q D_{p}}{N_{D B}} \tag{2.17}
\end{equation*}
$$
