description:The illustration details the functioning of a pnp BJT in forward active mode, highlighting the movement of various currents: i_E, i_B, i_C, i_EB, i_BB, and i_BC. The emitter-base voltage (VEB) is around 0.7V, and the base-collector voltage (VBC) is at least 0.2V.
FIGURE 2.11 Relevant currents in a pnp BJT operating in the forward active mode.
Here, $D_{p}$ represents the hole diffusivity, and $N_{D B}$ denotes the donor concentration in the base. Additionally, we have
$$
\begin{equation*}
\beta_{F}=\frac{1}{\frac{D_{n}}{D_{p}} \frac{N_{D B}}{N_{A E}} \frac{W_{B}}{W_{E}}+\frac{W_{B}^{2}}{2 \tau_{p} D_{p}}} \tag{2.18}
\end{equation*}
$$
where $D_{n}$ is the electron diffusivity, $N_{D B}$ is the donor concentration in the base, $N_{A E}$ is the acceptor concentration in the emitter, and $\tau_{p}$ is the average hole lifetime in the base.
Equations (2.11) and (2.17) highlight an intriguing aspect, namely, that the scale factor $I_{s}$ is directly proportional to the diffusivity ($D_{n}$ or $D_{p}$) of the charges driving the primary current in the BJT. This is expected, given that the collector current is diffusion-driven. In the subsequent chapter on MOSFETs, we will encounter a similar scale factor known as the transconductance parameter $k$, which is proportional to the mobility ($\mu_{n}$ or $\mu_{p}$) of the charges responsible for the main current in the device. This difference arises because MOSFET current is of the drift type. Figure 1.37 indicates that for a specific doping density, electron mobility and diffusivity are two to three times greater than their hole counterparts. Consequently, npn BJTs are typically favored over pnp types, and n-channel FETs are preferred over p-channel varieties.

