Equations (2.11) and (2.17) highlight an intriguing aspect: the scale factor $I_{s}$ is directly proportional to the diffusivity ($D_{n}$ or $D_{p}$) of the charges driving the main current in the BJT. This is expected, given that the collector current is diffusion-driven. In the subsequent chapter on MOSFETs, we will encounter a similar scale factor, termed the transconductance parameter $k$, which is proportional to the mobility ($\mu_{n}$ or $\mu_{p}$) of the charges responsible for the primary current in the device. This distinction arises because MOSFET current is of the drift type. Figure 1.37 indicates that, for a specific doping density, electron mobility and diffusivity are two to three times greater than those of holes. Consequently, npn BJTs are typically favored over pnp types, and n-channel FETs are preferred over p-channel variants.

