Figure 2.13a illustrates a PSpice circuit designed to depict the $i_{C}-v_{B E}$ characteristic of the 2N2222 npn BJT, utilizing the model available in PSpice's library (refer to Appendix 2A). The outcome, presented in Fig. 2.13b, is the well-known exponential curve forecasted by Eq. (2.10), with a slight alteration to be addressed later in conjunction with Eq. (2.21). The PSpice model employs $I_{s}=14.34 \mathrm{fA}$. It is important to remember that the B-E junction behaves similarly to a standard $p n$ diode, with the key difference being that nearly all electrons injected into the base are directed to the collector rather than the base terminal. As a result, all characteristics displayed by the $p n$ junction's $i-v$ behavior are also applicable to the BJT's $i_{C}-v_{B E}$ characteristic. Specifically, the following heuristic rules are relevant for BJTs:
- To achieve an octave change in $i_{C}$, $v_{B E}$ must be altered by 18 mV (18-mV Rule).
- To achieve a decade change in $i_{C}$, $v_{B E}$ must be altered by 60 mV (60-mV Rule).
- The voltage drop $V_{B E}$ exhibits a temperature coefficient of approximately $-2 \mathrm{mV} /{ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ (-2-mV Rule).
The slope of the $i_{C}-V_{B E}$ curve at a specific operating point $Q=Q\left(I_{C}, V_{B E}\right)$ is termed $g_{m}$, representing the transconductance (in A/V),
$$
\begin{equation*}
g_{m}=\left.\frac{\partial i_{C}}{\partial v_{B E}}\right|_{Q} \tag{2.19}
\end{equation*}
$$
By differentiating Eq. (2.10), we can easily derive
$$
\begin{equation*}
g_{m}=\frac{I_{C}}{V_{T}} \tag{2.20}
\end{equation*}
$$
This formula enables us to compute the BJT's transconductance at any bias current $I_{C}$. For instance, at $I_{C}=1 \mathrm{~mA}$, $g_{m}$ equals $38 \mathrm{~mA} / \mathrm{V}$, which is often expressed as $g_{m}=1 /(26 \Omega)$.
(Readers familiar with MOSFETs may notice a similarity with the MOSFET's transconductance, expressed as $g_{m}=I_{D} /\left(0.5 V_{O V}\right)$, where $V_{O V}$ is the overdrive voltage required to maintain a specific drain current $I_{D}$. Typically, $0.5 V_{O V}$ is much greater than $V_{T}$, so for the same bias current, a FET generally exhibits a lower transconductance than a BJT. This is a notable disadvantage of FETs compared to BJTs, particularly in the design of high-gain amplifiers.)
